caption.text:
Regulations, CEO tenure, and governance outcomes.
This table examines the effect of the CEO's tenure on board independence, CEO-chair duality, and compensation for years before and after 2002 when new regulations began to require firms to maintain majority independent boards. The sample is the same as that in
Table 1
, except for column 3, in which the sample is from 1936 to 2011 and conditions on CEO compensation data. “Post 2002” is an indicator variable equal to one for years equal to or after 2002, and zero for years before 2002. The dependent variables are independence ratio, an indicator for CEO-chair duality, and the log of the CEO's current compensation in columns 1, 2, and 3, respectively. Firms with only one reported director are excluded from the sample. Firm × post-2002 period and year fixed effects are used throughout the table. All standard errors are adjusted for sample clustering at the firm level. *, **, and *** represent results significant at the 10%, 5%, and 1% levels, respectively.

caption.text:
CEO tenure, chair duality, and compensation.
This table presents the relations between the CEO's tenure and CEO-chair duality (columns 1–2) or total current compensation including salary and bonus (columns 3–4). The sample is the same as that in
Table 1
, except for columns 3 and 4, in which the sample is from 1936 to 2011 and conditions on CEO compensation data. Columns 2 and 4 measure CEO tenure effects using the instrumental variable approach of
Altonji and Shakotko (1987)
, which, at each point in time, reflects the proportion of a given CEO's ultimate tenure. These columns display within-firm R-squared, while columns 1 and 3 show total R-squared. Firm and year fixed effects are included in all specifications. All standard errors are adjusted for sample clustering at the firm level. *, **, and *** represent results significant at the 10%, 5%, and 1% levels, respectively.
